1
00:00:05,860 --> 00:00:08,802
My name is Jason Weiser, and for the last four years,

2
00:00:09,063 --> 00:00:13,707
I've been teaching a crazy pants course at Tufts University called Game Design,

3
00:00:14,388 --> 00:00:19,452
which is actually tabletop game design, alternate reality game design,

4
00:00:19,592 --> 00:00:23,076
game testing, introduction to the Unity game engine and C-sharp programming,

5
00:00:23,756 --> 00:00:26,999
intro to 3D art and animation, intro to 2D art and UI,

6
00:00:27,420 --> 00:00:32,244
intro to audio for games, paper prototyping, level design, including rational game design.

7
00:00:32,779 --> 00:00:38,406
And encounter building, VR tools and considerations, team building and communication, digital game

8
00:00:38,446 --> 00:00:42,451
prototyping, pipeline development, modes of team management, marketing, industry networking,

9
00:00:43,012 --> 00:00:43,432
and more.

10
00:00:45,800 --> 00:00:50,901
This past fall, I described this course to the excellent Mr. Ian Schreiber, who's on

11
00:00:50,921 --> 00:00:55,821
the board of the Education Summit, and his response boiled down to, this course of yours

12
00:00:55,961 --> 00:00:58,162
breaks all the rules I know for game education.

13
00:00:58,642 --> 00:01:02,863
I always tell people to learn one thing at a time, otherwise you're going to end up frustrated

14
00:01:02,883 --> 00:01:05,903
with a doomed project, and yet you just mash it all together and go.

15
00:01:06,543 --> 00:01:08,864
In my head, I can't imagine how this could possibly work.

16
00:01:09,024 --> 00:01:13,765
Do you ever get any decent quality games out of the class, or is it 100% train wrecks and

17
00:01:13,785 --> 00:01:14,465
learning by failure?

18
00:01:15,045 --> 00:01:19,989
I'm not doing a particularly good Ian imitation, but in other words,

19
00:01:20,409 --> 00:01:23,892
who would ever want to take this circus and who would ever want to teach it?

20
00:01:27,611 --> 00:01:32,072
And I said to him, actually, all the projects succeed as engaging and playable prototypes,

21
00:01:32,293 --> 00:01:35,634
and many are really original, and some have gone on to be published on the Steam and the

22
00:01:35,714 --> 00:01:36,094
App Stores.

23
00:01:36,754 --> 00:01:40,335
And then last month, he asked me to deliver a talk where I prove this can work in front

24
00:01:40,355 --> 00:01:41,155
of hundreds of people.

25
00:01:41,696 --> 00:01:43,716
And, in fact, we got a couple hundred of you.

26
00:01:44,096 --> 00:01:44,596
So here we are.

27
00:01:45,817 --> 00:01:46,577
Thank you for being here.

28
00:01:48,298 --> 00:01:49,678
I should mention a couple of things.

29
00:01:50,578 --> 00:01:52,239
Please turn off your audio devices.

30
00:01:53,099 --> 00:01:56,680
And when you get your eval thingy, please fill out the eval thingy.

31
00:01:58,866 --> 00:02:01,950
So a bit of background, I'm an animator and game designer and educator.

32
00:02:02,130 --> 00:02:05,314
I animate for games and museums and robots and television.

33
00:02:06,936 --> 00:02:10,420
And I'm the creative director of Yaya Play Games, where I design stuff with my daughter,

34
00:02:10,880 --> 00:02:13,543
including the award-winning card game Monsters in the Elevator.

35
00:02:16,707 --> 00:02:18,629
And for the last 25 years, I've been teaching.

36
00:02:19,648 --> 00:02:24,375
In hindsight, I can see that my early teaching career courses had a scope problem.

37
00:02:24,976 --> 00:02:28,982
I started in Teach for America at a Baltimore school for students who had dropped out and

38
00:02:29,222 --> 00:02:30,143
asked to return.

39
00:02:30,836 --> 00:02:35,498
And being serious about education for the first time, many wanted as much as I could

40
00:02:35,518 --> 00:02:35,859
give them.

41
00:02:36,399 --> 00:02:40,801
So I taught international dance and art alongside creative writing and literature.

42
00:02:41,301 --> 00:02:45,503
And I thought my job was to pack my courses to the limit of what they could manage.

43
00:02:46,304 --> 00:02:50,426
When my classes got a reputation as the most demanding in the department, the department

44
00:02:50,446 --> 00:02:51,486
gave me the top students.

45
00:02:52,107 --> 00:02:54,008
And this did not incline me to reduce scope.

46
00:02:57,296 --> 00:03:01,757
And then at the Art Institutes, my students were entirely dedicated to the fields of games

47
00:03:01,817 --> 00:03:04,157
and animation and wanted everything I had to offer.

48
00:03:04,658 --> 00:03:09,879
And my goal in every course, no matter how introductory, was to maximize their portfolio

49
00:03:09,939 --> 00:03:10,319
output.

50
00:03:10,959 --> 00:03:16,900
So, in a just 10-week intro to 3D modeling course, we would create full portfolio-ready

51
00:03:17,020 --> 00:03:22,301
photographic room interiors and two full high-detailed characters in an intro course.

52
00:03:23,165 --> 00:03:24,207
My students did not sleep.

53
00:03:24,948 --> 00:03:29,933
One student at that time described my teaching style, and this is a metaphor, there was no

54
00:03:29,994 --> 00:03:35,220
touching involved, that I would grab them by the ears, place my foot on their face,

55
00:03:35,780 --> 00:03:36,601
and knowledge!

56
00:03:40,017 --> 00:03:43,779
This approach seemed to be validated at Pixar Animation Studios,

57
00:03:43,819 --> 00:03:46,420
where I taught a workshop for the layout team in summer of 2005.

58
00:03:47,340 --> 00:03:49,601
I built a crazy in-depth course,

59
00:03:50,241 --> 00:03:52,642
and they tirelessly devoured everything I gave.

60
00:03:53,223 --> 00:03:55,864
So eventually I had to pry their fingers off the keyboards

61
00:03:55,904 --> 00:03:56,864
to get them to take a break.

62
00:03:59,645 --> 00:04:02,867
I thought, this is how to teach the subjects of animation and games.

63
00:04:03,387 --> 00:04:05,228
You stuff the students until they burst.

64
00:04:09,160 --> 00:04:14,322
But I changed priorities around 2011 when I started teaching at other colleges where

65
00:04:14,342 --> 00:04:16,842
the students had many interests beyond my subjects.

66
00:04:17,542 --> 00:04:19,443
They did not want everything I could give them.

67
00:04:19,963 --> 00:04:24,824
So Intro to 3D became more of a minimum viable product to show competency.

68
00:04:24,964 --> 00:04:27,805
Just one hard surface and one organic object.

69
00:04:28,645 --> 00:04:33,007
And we animated using industry rigs, and my classes no longer took over their lives.

70
00:04:33,587 --> 00:04:39,188
The goals of my courses switched from massive portfolio content to concept mastery and confidence

71
00:04:39,248 --> 00:04:41,129
building with small scoped projects.

72
00:04:41,649 --> 00:04:45,970
So they felt empowered to take the concepts further outside of the course if they chose.

73
00:04:48,911 --> 00:04:49,891
And then Tufts happened.

74
00:04:51,191 --> 00:04:55,633
I casually emailed a friend in the Tufts computer science department asking, what are you folks

75
00:04:55,673 --> 00:04:56,313
doing with games?

76
00:04:59,744 --> 00:05:01,328
And he invited me to pitch the department.

77
00:05:03,492 --> 00:05:06,398
Now usually when I design curriculum for new game development programs,

78
00:05:06,458 --> 00:05:09,845
I follow a somewhat typical model with five or six courses.

79
00:05:10,433 --> 00:05:15,295
There is tabletop game design to learn mechanics and how to organize humans into playful experiences.

80
00:05:15,915 --> 00:05:20,977
And level design where we learn a digital game engine like Unity, a course on game environment

81
00:05:21,057 --> 00:05:26,059
art, a course on programming and prototyping, their first small original digital game, and

82
00:05:26,079 --> 00:05:28,520
then a capstone semester or two on team production.

83
00:05:29,260 --> 00:05:34,122
And as mentioned in Ian's feedback, each topic is taught on its own to grow skills in that

84
00:05:34,282 --> 00:05:34,822
one area.

85
00:05:36,627 --> 00:05:40,288
I suggested this to my friend at Tufts, a multi-course curriculum in games in their

86
00:05:40,328 --> 00:05:44,010
computer science department, and he said, how about you just try one class?

87
00:05:45,150 --> 00:05:48,292
And since it was for the computer science department, they would expect it to include

88
00:05:48,332 --> 00:05:49,072
a lot of programming.

89
00:05:50,593 --> 00:05:56,455
So I thought, that's four game courses stuffed into one class, and that's already crazy,

90
00:05:56,915 --> 00:05:58,436
so why not make it the full five?

91
00:06:01,098 --> 00:06:05,199
In my interview with the CS department chair, I did not emphasize that my course would be

92
00:06:05,259 --> 00:06:08,380
five semesters of traditional game design education in one term.

93
00:06:09,200 --> 00:06:13,741
I promised to teach her students how to think and plan before they code, and that they would

94
00:06:13,781 --> 00:06:16,261
experience a team software development pipeline.

95
00:06:16,681 --> 00:06:17,461
And she said yes.

96
00:06:18,222 --> 00:06:23,222
But it was made clear to me that this was an experiment, and if the course was not a

97
00:06:23,262 --> 00:06:25,523
big hit with the students, it would not be repeated.

98
00:06:26,023 --> 00:06:28,443
This crazy class had to work the first time.

99
00:06:29,486 --> 00:06:32,771
And personally, having spent a few years making manageable courses

100
00:06:32,971 --> 00:06:35,876
after a decade of crazy scoped ones, I wanted my students

101
00:06:35,916 --> 00:06:40,302
to leave this course feeling fulfilled and happy and not burned out.

102
00:06:42,773 --> 00:06:47,535
To do this, I asked for teaching assistance to offer coding labs and a flexible classroom

103
00:06:47,555 --> 00:06:52,377
that allowed us to move tables to switch between group work and play testing and lecture.

104
00:06:53,017 --> 00:06:57,959
I built every single assignment around teamwork to support student motivation and creativity,

105
00:06:58,400 --> 00:07:02,941
but also to give every student a net to catch them.

106
00:07:04,002 --> 00:07:07,370
with each other and supportive lessons in improving their teamwork.

107
00:07:07,650 --> 00:07:12,982
It wasn't just, okay, you know how to be teams because you're humans. We would teach them how to work with each other.

108
00:07:14,660 --> 00:07:19,963
I built a robust course website which offers clear expectations and resources, a detailed

109
00:07:20,023 --> 00:07:25,146
weekly schedule and homework reminders, lecture notes, assignment rubrics, tutorial videos

110
00:07:25,186 --> 00:07:29,548
to review the tools at their own pace, examples from past students, and sources for further

111
00:07:29,568 --> 00:07:29,868
learning.

112
00:07:30,389 --> 00:07:35,912
This site allows students to see the full scope of the course and so feel some control

113
00:07:36,052 --> 00:07:37,012
over their experience.

114
00:07:37,553 --> 00:07:39,754
This is at madwomb.com slash tufts.

115
00:07:39,994 --> 00:07:41,855
You are all welcome to take whatever you want.

116
00:07:45,305 --> 00:07:50,027
Finally, I used what I call stacking theory to structure the lessons.

117
00:07:51,968 --> 00:07:56,991
Stacking theory understands that students only learn one thing well at a time,

118
00:07:57,451 --> 00:08:03,554
but proposes that if students only learn, oops, proposes that if students are exposed

119
00:08:03,594 --> 00:08:07,176
to more things in the same class meeting without deadline pressure,

120
00:08:07,637 --> 00:08:10,958
they can get curious and begin to absorb these others.

121
00:08:11,959 --> 00:08:14,540
Here is how the core topics are stacked in this course.

122
00:08:17,037 --> 00:08:18,998
The class meets once a week for three hours.

123
00:08:19,479 --> 00:08:21,660
We discuss and practice the one critical topic

124
00:08:21,680 --> 00:08:23,921
for that week's homework, and you can see the stars,

125
00:08:24,582 --> 00:08:27,603
and introduce two to three other ideas or tool sets

126
00:08:27,623 --> 00:08:28,684
that will be important later.

127
00:08:28,804 --> 00:08:31,346
So for example, a month before anyone will need

128
00:08:31,386 --> 00:08:33,307
to make anything in 3D for homework,

129
00:08:33,647 --> 00:08:35,728
we start learning basic modeling and texturing.

130
00:08:38,350 --> 00:08:40,391
By the time these concepts are needed for homework,

131
00:08:40,431 --> 00:08:42,032
they have been explored multiple times

132
00:08:42,092 --> 00:08:43,693
with room for confidence building success.

133
00:08:44,263 --> 00:08:47,104
and opportunities for wrong turns to be corrected,

134
00:08:47,504 --> 00:08:49,325
which reduces stress and frustration.

135
00:08:50,005 --> 00:08:53,346
By the time we reach final game production after midterms,

136
00:08:53,747 --> 00:08:56,668
we've experienced most of the tools needed to accomplish it.

137
00:08:58,949 --> 00:09:00,109
This is a high-level summary,

138
00:09:00,149 --> 00:09:01,610
but we're about to go into this in detail.

139
00:09:07,532 --> 00:09:09,613
So imagine with me a student, Samantha.

140
00:09:11,007 --> 00:09:15,791
Two weeks before the term begins, she gets a welcome email asking to share about games

141
00:09:15,831 --> 00:09:19,915
she loves and, because most of her classmates have not played modern board games, links

142
00:09:19,975 --> 00:09:23,478
to Wil Wheaton's tabletop show so they don't think we are just talking about Candyland

143
00:09:23,518 --> 00:09:24,078
and Monopoly.

144
00:09:26,500 --> 00:09:31,185
The first six weeks focus on tabletop games and the students work in two-week teams.

145
00:09:32,265 --> 00:09:36,188
On day one, we distinguish between mechanics and story to focus on mechanics.

146
00:09:36,908 --> 00:09:41,732
Samantha forms a team with three other students and designs a tabletop game inspired by weird

147
00:09:41,772 --> 00:09:42,633
boards and toys.

148
00:09:43,213 --> 00:09:47,216
They read from Jesse Schell's Art of Game Design and meet outside of class to work on

149
00:09:47,257 --> 00:09:47,677
their game.

150
00:09:50,219 --> 00:09:55,023
Week two, we practice playtesting their games to find the fun and discuss radical revision

151
00:09:55,063 --> 00:09:56,664
to refocus around that fun.

152
00:09:57,324 --> 00:10:00,347
They meet outside of class again to revise mechanics and story.

153
00:10:01,233 --> 00:10:03,134
One of my favorite examples of this lesson

154
00:10:03,455 --> 00:10:05,837
interpreted this Tree of Life game board

155
00:10:06,057 --> 00:10:09,059
as an asymmetrical combat between a computer antivirus

156
00:10:09,480 --> 00:10:10,560
and an invading AI.

157
00:10:11,081 --> 00:10:13,363
And having used these boards now for many, many years,

158
00:10:14,143 --> 00:10:16,645
it's amazing how we never get sick of what they create,

159
00:10:17,766 --> 00:10:19,528
as I'm sure many of you have discovered in your classes.

160
00:10:21,730 --> 00:10:25,092
Week three, Samantha forms a second two-week team,

161
00:10:25,532 --> 00:10:27,533
and they are asked to disrupt an existing game

162
00:10:27,553 --> 00:10:28,334
into something new.

163
00:10:28,774 --> 00:10:30,075
And we get disruptions of everything

164
00:10:30,115 --> 00:10:32,517
from chess and sari to uno and duck-duck goose.

165
00:10:33,197 --> 00:10:35,959
One of my favorite examples of this was Sand Wizard of Catan.

166
00:10:36,759 --> 00:10:38,200
The desert is placed at the center.

167
00:10:38,781 --> 00:10:41,422
When a player rolls seven, the robber does not move.

168
00:10:42,043 --> 00:10:44,264
Instead, the player chooses one of the hexes

169
00:10:44,284 --> 00:10:46,385
around the desert and flips the number disk

170
00:10:46,886 --> 00:10:47,906
so the desert spreads.

171
00:10:52,755 --> 00:10:57,741
At home, Samantha and her team read J. McGonigal's Reality is Broken, and then we spend an hour

172
00:10:57,801 --> 00:11:03,507
of week four brainstorming and presenting an alternate reality game to solve a misery.

173
00:11:06,567 --> 00:11:10,550
With three hours of class time a week, we take one hour on software tools.

174
00:11:11,070 --> 00:11:15,834
So weeks three and four, they follow me in tutorials for Unity 3D and 2D projects,

175
00:11:16,214 --> 00:11:19,357
where she learns to use scripting and physics and feedback

176
00:11:19,417 --> 00:11:21,879
to make basic platformers and collection games.

177
00:11:22,579 --> 00:11:25,862
Week four, she makes Rollaball, the Unity tutorial at home.

178
00:11:26,383 --> 00:11:29,085
My three TAs start running Codelabs a few times a week,

179
00:11:29,165 --> 00:11:31,907
so Samantha can get help and learn more Unity tools.

180
00:11:33,415 --> 00:11:39,056
Week five, Samantha forms her third team to make a final tabletop project based on the

181
00:11:39,096 --> 00:11:40,517
routines of a workplace.

182
00:11:41,237 --> 00:11:46,218
And we get games about window washers and airline traffic controllers and way too many

183
00:11:46,258 --> 00:11:46,759
baristas.

184
00:11:49,159 --> 00:11:53,160
Here you can see what was handed in just a couple weeks ago of the current class, the

185
00:11:53,201 --> 00:11:57,542
window washing game, an asymmetrical game where you're either the window washer trying

186
00:11:57,562 --> 00:12:01,263
to clean the windows or the robber trying to hide the evidence of their past crimes

187
00:12:01,763 --> 00:12:03,123
and you're trying to clean to catch them.

188
00:12:07,123 --> 00:12:10,705
Also week five, I teach the basics of 3D Maya to Unity pipeline.

189
00:12:11,245 --> 00:12:14,707
And week six, we learn about making Unity builds and VR tools.

190
00:12:15,167 --> 00:12:21,470
And then Sam's team gets one week, until week seven, to turn their workplace game digital.

191
00:12:22,390 --> 00:12:25,911
With a stated zero expectation of success.

192
00:12:27,158 --> 00:12:31,321
The point of that one week is to just get in as much as they can and make as many mistakes

193
00:12:31,381 --> 00:12:31,961
as possible.

194
00:12:32,341 --> 00:12:38,084
A previous class actually asked for this lesson, to make a lot of mistakes on an original game

195
00:12:38,284 --> 00:12:39,685
before the final project.

196
00:12:40,906 --> 00:12:42,827
And it's been amazing in the years since we've done this.

197
00:12:45,208 --> 00:12:49,971
Week seven, Samantha's team shows off their first original digital game, and I'm always

198
00:12:50,031 --> 00:12:52,012
impressed by how much they actually get working.

199
00:12:53,199 --> 00:12:58,422
Sam then gets a review of all design topics covered so far and is encouraged to think

200
00:12:58,462 --> 00:13:02,485
of new ways to move and interact and to get playful with visuals and premise.

201
00:13:03,406 --> 00:13:08,349
She then gets 30 minutes of walking around brainstorming with her classmates with some

202
00:13:08,489 --> 00:13:10,671
silent reflection occasionally in that time.

203
00:13:11,688 --> 00:13:15,971
Then everyone gets a white note card to write down their final idea,

204
00:13:16,531 --> 00:13:20,193
and Sam chooses a colored sticky note for the main production role

205
00:13:20,213 --> 00:13:22,314
she plans to fulfill on the final project.

206
00:13:22,915 --> 00:13:26,196
Code, art, audio, or project management.

207
00:13:27,017 --> 00:13:28,878
Everyone participates in design.

208
00:13:29,578 --> 00:13:34,641
So these are just the production roles outside of design concerns.

209
00:13:38,253 --> 00:13:41,935
Then Sam gets 45 seconds to stand up and pitch her idea to the class.

210
00:13:42,415 --> 00:13:47,218
She tapes the white card with her idea to the wall, and when all who want to pitch have

211
00:13:47,238 --> 00:13:51,200
done so, everyone votes with their colored sticky notes for the project they want to

212
00:13:51,240 --> 00:13:51,420
make.

213
00:13:52,181 --> 00:13:57,344
This is the system the MIT Game Lab uses for the Global Game Jam, and it's stolen wholeheartedly

214
00:13:57,384 --> 00:13:57,644
from them.

215
00:13:58,678 --> 00:14:03,100
In a class of 40 students, we get around 30 pitches and make about 8 games.

216
00:14:04,001 --> 00:14:08,143
I rebalance roles if needed to make sure every group has programmers and artists, and in

217
00:14:08,183 --> 00:14:10,344
this way, final teams are decided.

218
00:14:11,124 --> 00:14:15,767
If Sam's idea was chosen, I remind her to expect it will change dramatically in the

219
00:14:15,807 --> 00:14:21,069
process of iteration and testing and revision, so I advise let it go and trust the process

220
00:14:21,189 --> 00:14:21,790
and her new team.

221
00:14:26,870 --> 00:14:29,570
The teams then get, in the second half of the semester,

222
00:14:30,291 --> 00:14:33,011
one week to draft a design doc and paper prototypes

223
00:14:33,091 --> 00:14:35,812
for user stories, and then one week

224
00:14:35,852 --> 00:14:38,473
to get as much of the game working in Unity as they can,

225
00:14:39,753 --> 00:14:41,974
two more weeks to complete a working prototype,

226
00:14:42,694 --> 00:14:44,274
and then three weeks to build that out

227
00:14:44,354 --> 00:14:46,655
to a fuller game with multiple levels and more

228
00:14:46,735 --> 00:14:47,795
polished art and audio.

229
00:14:48,315 --> 00:14:51,496
We play test every week and significantly adjust the game

230
00:14:51,556 --> 00:14:53,377
plan at least a few times per team.

231
00:14:57,605 --> 00:14:59,306
And during this latter half of the semester,

232
00:14:59,386 --> 00:15:01,186
Sam gets lessons in basic Photoshop,

233
00:15:01,226 --> 00:15:03,167
and user interface, and audio composition,

234
00:15:03,547 --> 00:15:04,987
and three weeks of level design.

235
00:15:05,947 --> 00:15:08,428
For two weeks, at the very end, we discuss marketing,

236
00:15:08,808 --> 00:15:11,168
and Sam and her team prepare a trailer and website

